    body: "Clemency (clementia) is a virtue allied to temperance by which a person in authority moderates the severity of punishment, not from weakness or indifference to justice, but from a deliberate choice to temper severity with mercy. St. Thomas Aquinas treats clemency as a potential part of temperance because it moderates the passion of anger that inclines toward excessive punishment. Clemency does not eliminate punishment — that would be a failure of justice — but ensures that punishment is proportionate, rehabilitative, and humane. It is closely related to meekness (which moderates anger) but is specifically concerned with the exercise of punitive authority. God Himself is the supreme exemplar of clemency: 'The Lord is merciful and gracious, slow to anger and abounding in steadfast love' (Psalm 103:8).",
