    body: "Spiritual childhood is the way of holiness taught preeminently by St. Therese of Lisieux, Doctor of the Church, who called it her 'Little Way.' It is rooted in Christ's words: 'Unless you turn and become like children, you will never enter the kingdom of heaven' (Matthew 18:3). Spiritual childhood is characterized by radical trust in God's merciful love, acceptance of one's own smallness and weakness, simplicity of intention, and the abandonment of all spiritual ambition beyond loving God in the present moment. It is not immaturity or naivety but a profoundly theological disposition that takes God at His word: if He is truly a loving Father, then the proper response is the total trust of a child. St. Therese's Little Way was validated by the Church as an authentic path to holiness accessible to all.",
    example: "St. Therese compared herself to a small child at the foot of a staircase, unable to climb even the first step toward holiness — but instead of despairing, she trusted that God, like a loving Father, would bend down, pick her up, and carry her to the top.",
