    body: "Catholic moral theology distinguishes between acquired virtues — habits of good action developed through repeated human effort (as Aristotle taught) — and infused virtues — supernatural habits given directly by God at Baptism, enabling acts that surpass natural capacity. The theological virtues (faith, hope, charity) are always infused, since they direct us to God as known by revelation. The cardinal virtues (prudence, justice, fortitude, temperance) can be both acquired (through practice) and infused (by grace). The infused moral virtues give the soul a supernatural orientation, while the acquired moral virtues provide the experiential facility to act on that orientation. The two operate in concert: grace perfects nature, and infused virtues build upon and elevate the acquired virtues. Without infused virtues, the soul cannot merit supernatural rewards; without acquired virtues, the person may have the supernatural orientation but lack the practical capacity to act on it.",
